  <introduction>
    <p>
      Introduction goes here.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        The infinite series <m>\DS\sum_{k=1}^{\infty} a_{k}</m> is defined as the limit of the sequence of partial sums (if it exists):
        <me>
          \sum_{k=1}^{\infty} a_{k}=\limit{n\to\infty}\sum_{k=1}^{n} a_{k}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Series limit laws
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Divergence test: If <m>a_{k}\not\to 0</m>, then <m>\DS\sum a_{k}</m> diverges.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        If a series has all nonnegative terms, then either it converges or it diverges to infinity.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Comparison test: Assume <m>0\le a_{k}\le b_{k}</m> for all <m>k</m>.
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              If <m>\DS\sum b_{k}</m> converges, then <m>\DS\sum a_{k}</m> converges.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              If <m>\DS\sum a_{k}</m> diverges, then <m>\DS\sum b_{k}</m> diverges.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        The harmonic series diverges.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Integral test: If <m>a_{n}=f(n)</m>, then <m>\DS\sum a_{n}</m> converges if and only if <m>\DS\int_{1}^{\infty} f(x)\dd{x}</m> converges.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        <m>p</m>-series test: <m>\DS\sum \frac{1}{k^{p}}</m> converges if and only if <m>p>1</m>.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Limit comparison test: Assume <m>0\le a_{k}\le b_{k}</m> for all <m>k</m>.
        If
        <me>
          \limit{k\to\infty}\dfrac{a_{k}}{b_{k}}
        </me>
        where <m>0&#x3C;c&#x3C;\infty</m>, then <m>\DS\sum a_{k}</m> converges if and only if <m>\DS\sum b_{k}</m> converges.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
